Celebrate California&amp;#39;s Pioneer Heritage with the colorful Kit Carson Mountain Men.&amp;nbsp;

&amp;nbsp;

In the California Gold Country, the Kit Carson Mountain Men are best known for leading wagon train reenactments, including the Kit Carson Days Wagon Train on Highway 88, the Highway 50 Wagon Train, and now, Days of 49 Wagon Train along historic Highway 49.

&amp;nbsp;

Kit Carson Mountain Men perform every year inside Frontier Village at Amador County&amp;#39;s Fair, which runs the last full weekend in July. They can be seen in the Italian Picnic Parade in Sutter Creek the first weekend in June, and at Christmas Delights Friday and Saturday after Thanksgiving.

&amp;nbsp;

For 75 years, the Kit Carson Mountain Men have seen many unique participants and have accumulated more stories than can be retold.

&amp;nbsp;

Originally, this group of men called to preserve the traditions of early American fur traders, were called the &amp;ldquo;Whiskerinos.&amp;rdquo; The Whiskerinos changed their name to Kit Carson Mountain Men and incorporated in 1940. &amp;ldquo;Mountain Honeys&amp;rdquo; -- later changed to Women of the West &amp;ndash; also participate in reenactments with the Kit Carson Mountain Men.

&amp;nbsp;

Wagon Train 2014 Video:

YouTube.com/DaysOf49WagonTrain/Friday2014

&amp;nbsp;

For information about Kit Carson Mountain Men: fashionstables@comcast.net

&amp;nbsp;




Numerous well-known individuals have visited the Mountain Men in Amador County including Andy Griffith, John Wayne, Ronald Reagan, John Ford, Ken Curtis and more.

&amp;nbsp;

Ronald Reagan and Amador&amp;rsquo;s Saddle: When Ronald Reagan was the Governor of California, local horseman Harold Cummins provided Reagan with a spotted Appaloosa horse. The horse was renamed &amp;ldquo;Amador&amp;rdquo; in honor of the Mountain Men. Reagan, also a member of the Mountain Men, rode Amador in parades throughout the region, including the annual Kit Carson Days parade in Jackson. The mountain men rode behind Reagan in the parade and current Mountain Man President John Queirolo inherited Amador&amp;rsquo;s saddle.

&amp;nbsp;

The Mountain Men and The Queen:&amp;nbsp; The Queen of England came to Sacramento in 1983 and specifically requested to see Sutter&amp;rsquo;s Fort and the Mountain Men, after reading a magazine article about the Mountain Men. In Jackson, during a Mountain Men meeting, a stranger walked in wearing a suit and tie. When the men in their coonskin caps and buckskins saw him, they called out, &amp;ldquo;We don&amp;rsquo;t allow ties in here! Cut it off!&amp;rdquo; One of the Mountain Men, Bill Reed, cut off the man&amp;rsquo;s tie. However, when the man informed the boisterous group that he was with the FBI, sent by request of the President of the United States on behalf of the Queen of England, the Mountain Men quieted down. John Queirolo was in charge of the Queen&amp;rsquo;s visit and the organization of the Mountain Men to be her honor guard at Sutter&amp;rsquo;s Fort. After the Queen&amp;rsquo;s visit, Queirolo discovered that one of the Mountain Men, who had been in the club for 14 months, was an FBI agent sent to ensure the Queen&amp;rsquo;s safety.&amp;nbsp;

&amp;nbsp;

Thanks to the Amador Ledger Dispatch for background on the Kit Carson Mountain Men.

&amp;nbsp;

